{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"422ca8f1-2c4e-44e3-b239-e412e86270b3","content":"Here are the **3 evaluation performance issues** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (Line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions executes during **evaluation**, blocking the entire parse phase. This is expensive and non-cacheable. **Fix:** Move file reading to a target that runs at build time, or use a custom task.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Broad Glob Pattern (Line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. As the project grows (or if `node_modules`/large folders exist), this becomes a major bottleneck. **Fix:** Use a narrower glob (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds an evaluation pass. While 3 levels is manageable, this pattern can quickly escalate. Keep import depth shallow and consolidate where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Priority:** Issues #1 and #2 are the most impactful — file I/O stalls evaluation entirely, and overly broad globs scale poorly with directory size.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ffb9fbb-898e-4313-9fa8-6338282377de","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"5C01:27A376:1DF82AE:21D6EED:6A07CA27"},"id":"240d13e7-5c11-452d-afc0-ae5420936260","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:36:48.514Z","parentId":"aa907f19-5107-4852-9694-2e2605b32dda"}
